### Test Case 1: New Contact (No existing records)
POST http://localhost:8080/identify
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "lorraine@hillvalley.edu",
  "phoneNumber": "123456"
}

### Expected Response:
# {
#   "contact": {
#     "primaryContatctId": 1,
#     "emails": ["lorraine@hillvalley.edu"],
#     "phoneNumbers": ["123456"],
#     "secondaryContactIds": []
#   }
# }

---

### Test Case 2: New Information (Creates Secondary)
POST http://localhost:8080/identify
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "mcfly@hillvalley.edu",
  "phoneNumber": "123456"
}

### Expected Response:
# {
#   "contact": {
#     "primaryContatctId": 1,
#     "emails": ["lorraine@hillvalley.edu", "mcfly@hillvalley.edu"],
#     "phoneNumbers": ["123456"],
#     "secondaryContactIds": [2]
#   }
# }

---

### Test Case 3: Existing Contact (No new info)
POST http://localhost:8080/identify
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "lorraine@hillvalley.edu",
  "phoneNumber": "123456"
}

### Expected Response:
# Same as Test Case 2 (no new contact created)

---

### Test Case 4: Merge Two Primaries
# First create two separate primaries:

POST http://localhost:8080/identify
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "george@hillvalley.edu",
  "phoneNumber": "919191"
}

---

POST http://localhost:8080/identify
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "biffsucks@hillvalley.edu",
  "phoneNumber": "717171"
}

---

# Now merge them:
POST http://localhost:8080/identify
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "george@hillvalley.edu",
  "phoneNumber": "717171"
}

### Expected Response:
# Older primary remains, newer becomes secondary
# {
#   "contact": {
#     "primaryContatctId": 3,
#     "emails": ["george@hillvalley.edu", "biffsucks@hillvalley.edu"],
#     "phoneNumbers": ["919191", "717171"],
#     "secondaryContactIds": [4]
#   }
# }

---

